(4) Fable of Peleus and Ceyx (ll. 265—410). Jupiter becomes alarmed at the prophecy that Thetis will be the mother of a child who is to be greater than his father3 he accordingly allows Peleus to be her husband, instead of assuming that position himself. The offspring of the. marriage is Achilles. Peleus has had the misfortune to kill his brother Phocus, and accordingly goes to Ceyx of Trachis in order to be purified. He there learns that Daedalion, the brother of CeyX, has been changed into a hawk‚ and also that a wolf which has been sent by Psamatbe to revenge Phocus is destroying the herds. Thetis intercedes on behalt' of Peleus, and the Nereid Psamathe turns the wolf into stoue.

(5) Fable of Ceyx aud Alcyone. Ceyx is shipwrecked 011 his voyage to the oracle of Apollo at Claros, whither he had gone to consult about his brother’s fate. His body is cast up on the shore ot' his own country, aud is there discovered by his wife Alcyone, who had had a dream, sent by Somnus at Juno’s command, which revealed to her the fate of her husband. In despair at this confirma- tion of her dream, she casts herself into the sea; but the gods, 111 pity, change both her and her husband into king- fishers (ll. 410—748).

(6) Fable of Aesacus. The transformation of Ceyx and Alcyone into birds reminds the poet of another similar transforniation. Aesacus, the son of Priam and Alexim-hoe, is in love with aud pursues Hesperie, the daughter of the river-god Cebren. In endeavouring to escape she is bitten by a serpent, aud dies from the wound. Aesacus, through grief at her destruction, plunges into the sea, and is changed by Tethys into a bird called the diver.
